KDD Retro: Google Knowledge Vault and Topic Modeling

Introduction

One of URX's key mantras is "we are lifelong learners." To this end, the URX data science team recently attended the 2014 Knowledge Discover and Data mining (KDD) conference in New York. The conference was a whirlwind, four day tour of the latest research in data mining. The conference was composed of one day of full tutorials, three days of keynotes, lightning talks and poster sessions. The theme of these sessions was utilizing text information to improve knowledge inference. This encompasses a wide variety of text-based problems; topic modelling, structured knowledge extraction, bioinformatics, targeted advertising, and many, many more. In the wake of KDD14, we wanted to summarize a couple of our favourite programs and encourage feedback.

Google KV

One of the most exciting talks of the conference was a tutorial run by Evgeniy Gabrilovich (Google) and Antoine Bordes (Facebook) on Constructing and Mining Web-scale Knowledge Graphs. The two presenters split the tutorial into two sessions. The first session, run by Evgeniy, provided an overview of Freebase; a publicly available, structured knowledge graph of human information. Evgeniy delved into the uses of and challenges with maintaining such a large, diverse graph of knowledge. The second session, run by Antoine, focused on solutions to a few, important problems faced when growing large knowledge graphs.

Evgeniy began with an overview of the Google's Knowledge Vault, focusing on entity extraction, data fusion and resolving schema heterogeneity. His talk covers a range of questions: what is an entity, why does it need to be extracted, how do we trust it and how do we incorporate such learnings into a preexisting set of facts. We present our interpretation of Evgeniy's approach to these problems.

An entity is any piece of structured information that can be learned from any arbitrary data source. We restrict our focus to one schema for representing structured information - Resource Description Framework (RDF) triples. RDFs are a representation of an atomic unit of human knowledge in the triple form, (subject, predicate, value). For example, the sentence "Deadmau5 is an electronic artist" can be written in triple form (Deadmau5, is_a, electronic_artist). Not all sentences are so easily mapped into a RDF triple. Take the sentence "URX is a tech startup based in South Park, San Francisco". Within this sentence, there are a multitude of facts that can be extracted. For example:

(URX, is_a, start_up)
(URX, is_located, South_Park)
(South_Park, is_located, San_Francisco)
(San_Francisco, is_a, location)
...

Extracting structured facts from unstructured text is a complex problem! To this end, the information retrieval community relies heavily on Freebase: a large, freely available collection of RDF triples on human knowledge. Freebase itself is part of the greater semantic web using data from sources as diverse as DBpedia, musicbrainz and others .... In aggregate, Freebase contains approximately 637 million triples (facts) and is growing everyday.

One amazing consequence of representing human knowledge in RDF triples is that this form readily maps to a graph structure. Subjects and Values are nodes in the graph with edges labelled as the predicate. Once a graph the size of Freebase is built, classic graph operations can quickly identify facts, discover relevant content to a given subject, and even interpret questions.

This leads to the second question; why are structured, graph entities useful? The simplest answer can be discovered with a Google search for Lil Wayne's birthdate.

Google has recently started displaying cards of information to answer specific searches. In the above example, in response to the query lil wayne birthdate, a card containing the artist's birthdate and age is displayed. These facts are derived from Google's Knowledge Vault (GKV) - an extension of Freebase. Additional facts in the form of actions are displayed in a neighbouring card. These listen-actions link users to one of several music streaming sites. Structured facts such as (Lil_Wayne, listen, Google_play_link) and (Lil_Wayne, listen, Rhapsody_link) are contained in Freebase. Google's search engine surfaces these links after matching the user's query with Freebase entities.

Taking it one step further, Google also recommends similar artists (e.g. Drake, Niki Minaj and Eminem). Similar artists are learned from a combination of user search logs and Freebase. Google clusters users to discover that "users who search for X are likely to search for Y", a classical recommendation problem. Improvements are observed when Google fuses this information with entities discovered within linked data repositories. In this example we leverage the fact that the above individuals are connected in the knowledge graph through an "artist" vertex.

Beyond boosting and improving search quality, Evgeniy alluded to several more applications of such inference. Facebook Graph searches such as "People who like Harvard University and Basketball at work at Facebook" can be interpreted as a suite of facts. Each fact is matched against a combination of Facebook's internal data and Freebase's knowledge graph. Siri, Evi and other question answering intelligence can be powered using these ideas. The learners inside these technologies match user questions with Freebase facts and return these facts as answers.

Given that Freebase has been motivated as an important endeavour, Evgeniy proceeds to describe the history of building structured facts out of unstructured knowledge. He restricts the talk to discussions about extraction of human knowledge from textual clues derived from web pages. While mentioning that facts can be inferred from other data sources (images, sound, and even 3D generated worlds!), Freebase itself is principally derived from text and Linked Data. A major challenge in building and maintaining knowledge graphs is data linkage. We need to correlate features extracted from the largely unstructured internet with existing linked data. This is what forms the core of GKV: a pipeline for relating structured facts to unstructured information. The diagram below, taken from Evgeniy's talk, overviews the pipeline.

At the top, extraction of information is broken into two domains. The first, text extractors, answer the question what can we get from a web page? The second is Freebase priors; what is already known that can improve our ability to form facts?

Evgeniy mentions four distinct text extractors: text, Webmaster annotation's, Page structure and Tables. For details on each process see the KDD talk and referenced papers.

At a high level, text uses techniques learnt from decades of natural language processing and information retrieval. Using models that Google has trained over huge amounts of labelled data, words can be tagged with their intrinsic meanings - Locations, Names, etc.

Webmaster annotations leverage microdata and ontologies like Schema.org. Unfortunately, while quite a few sites use Schema.org markup, markup is often sparse and inaccurate. Nevertheless, Google treats Schema.org as any other machine learning feature, leaving it up to the ensemble learner to decide when the feature is useful.

Page structure methods extract the hierarchy of the HTML as features to learn structured information. Domains often re-use specific DOM elements when structuring their websites and we can exploit this to separate out boilerplate from interesting information. Once a small amount of information can be correlated with a specific DOM path, subsequent information can be confidently extracted.

Finally, tables on pages act as a wealth of structured facts. Wikipedia's entry on Jupiter contains a large table on the right hand side of the page (an infobox). If a table can be accurately identified and the enclosed information confidently extracted, a large number of structured facts can be deduced. One practical example, DBPedia is intimately linked with Freebass; may facts of the facts they share are derived from infobox extractions.

The theme of the above features is that individually, they're all noisy. Entity extractors built using any one feature would yield an inaccurate method. However, taken in combination, corrleations between the features can be learned to form an entity extractor more accuracte than any one, individual feature.

The same holds true for freebase priors. It's beyond the scope of this post to dive into the principles of deep neural networks and path ranking algorithms used to build these priors. At a cursory level, neural networks learn the underlying structure and representation of the information contained in Freebase objects. Path ranking algorithms leverage the inherent graph structure of freebase to boost fact finding.

As is common in data science, features gleaned from different domains are often fused via ensemble methods. GKV fuses extractors and priors using a final ensemble learner into the system they use today. To ensure these semi-supervised methods are accurate, Google computes the precision and recall of extracted facts using human evaluators.

Topic Modeling

A number of the research papers presented throughout the KDD sessions focused on clustering, topic modeling and unsupervised statistical methods. One commonality between many of these models is their use of Dirichlet Processes and Gibbs sampling as a means to help approach a variety of applications. It is worthwhile to delve deeper into these techniques and take a brief look at a selection of these papers, highlighting two in particular.

As a refresher, the Dirichlet Process is a method of assigning a probability distribution to a random variable whose domain is a set of probability distributions. This provides a flexible and fast method for approximating the true distribution of the observed random variable. The Hierarchical Dirichlet Process extends this notion, allowing for multiple layers of probability distributions to influence prior knowledge on inference. Gibbs sampling (commonly used as a means of Bayesian inference) is a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) algorithm for generating a sequence of data from a multivariate probability distribution (such as the Hierarchical Dirichlet Process). Such methods of generating sample data are useful when direct measurement of a random variable is difficult.

Chen and Liu presented a paper that provided an alternate method for incorporating prior domain knowledge to assist a topic model in extracting better topics from a corpus. For a classic LDA topic model, the accuracy and comprehensibility of the topics scales roughly with the number of documents in the corpus. Even for large corpora, unsupervised methods can yield less-than-optimal results; this has led to a rise in popularity of knowledge-based topic models with input from users. Common user feedback takes the form of a non-automated process with significant inaccuracies. Chen and Liu automate this process of incorporating prior domain knowledge by using an algorithm to mine both Must-Links (two words should be in the same topic) and Cannot-Links (two words should not be in the same topic). For a large collection composed of documents from N web domains, the algorithm uses the output of N domain-specific LDA topic models and unions the topics into a set S. Their next step is to find sets of words that appear together in multiple topics using the machine learning technique Frequent Itemset Mining (FIM) and use these Must-Links as prior knowledge for their AMC topic model. Chen and Liu collect Cannot-Links by finding sets of terms which rarely appear together in S. The AMC algorithm has the potential to add relevance out-of-the-box to any topic model and subsequently improve inference as it observes more information. We are looking forward to the application of AMC beyond the dataset that was used in the evaluation section of the paper.

Taking a more meta approach, Li. et al recognized the high computational costs associated with unsupervised statistical inference. The density of feature matrices increases with increased sample data; in fact, O(k) operations per word are required for k topics. Li proposed that dense, slowly-changing distributions can be approximated by a combination of a Metropolis-Hastings step (demonstrating an acceptance rate of ~90%) and Walkers alias method. Given that the paper proposes an algorithm that scales linearly with the number of topics in the document, Li demonstrates an order of magnitude speedup for algorithms such as the Hierarchical Dirichlet Process. In this paper, the use of Metropolis-Hasting is a clever tweak on the Gibbs Sampler approach given that the Gibbs Sampler is a specialized case of Metropolis-Hastings. Drawing from a distribution over n outcomes would typically require O(n) work, but it is possible to draw subsequent samples from the same distribution in O(1) time. This helps Li derive value from the key assumption that the distributions are slowly-changing, leading to a significant decrease in computational costs. This provides more flexibility to incorporate the Walker alias method and create what Li et al. has called the Metropolis-Hastings-Walker sampling.

Dundar et al. used Dirichlet-process Gaussian-mixture models (DPMs) and Gibbs Sampling to design a new clustering algorithm called ASPIRE for discovering rare, yet significant, reoccurring classes across a batch of samples. At its core, this non-parametric Bayesian algorithm simultaneously learns several DPMs where each individual DPM models the local distribution of a single class.

Liang et al. created a supervised approach to improve search result diversification and personalized web search. Although unsupervised methods are most common in the literature, Liangs approach infused a user-interest latent Dirichlet topic model learnt from features extracted from user queries. This method optimizes two distinct, opposing constraints for diversity and personalization via a Gibbs sampler method.

Wu et al. tackled the problem of tagging videos with time-synced descriptions using an LDA model. This topic model is built on crowd-sourced comments that were tagged on the video site Nico Nico Douga. To resolve some of the noise inherent in on-line comments, Wu developed an LDA model that incorporated priors on a user level (users comment style, preferences) as well as the temporal level (sequentially within a video) to capture latent topics. Finally, a Gibbs Sampler was used to infer the topic(s) present at each point in the video and derive a description phrase or set of keywords.

Buntine and Mishra developed high-performing non-parametric topic models exhibiting burstiness based on standard Gibbs sampling. In information retrieval, Burstiness is a measure of the likelihood of a word re-appearing within a document. Topic models which include priors on burstiness have been shown marginally more accurate than classic LDA methods. However, this comes at the expense of maintaining additional probability vectors for each word in each position in each document. The authors state that their methods are require twice the memory than that of methods not including burstiness.

Conclusion

This year's KDD was an information packed, whirlwind of a conference. We enjoyed both the number and variety of talks presented at both tutorial and lightning sessions. We'd love to hear your comments on the above topics and any other sessions you found useful. Please reach out to research@urx.com.
